50|$|The track {{stand or}} {{standstill}} {{is a technique}} that bicycle riders can use to maintain balance while their bicycle remains stationary or moves only minimal distances. The technique originated in track cycling and is now used by other types of cyclists wishing to stop {{for a short time}} without putting a foot on the ground, such as bike commuters at stop signs. To perform a track stand, a cyclist holds the cranks in an approximately horizontal position with the front <b>wheel</b> <b>steered</b> to the left or right, and pedals forward, and back {{in the case of a}} fixed-gear bicycle, which the <b>steered</b> front <b>wheel</b> converts into a side-to-side motion.|$|R
